      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As chief executive officer of Eclipse Laboratories, marketers of sunscreen products, I may be regarded as an unlikely proponent of measures to protect the earth's high ozone layer, which shields life from the sun's harmful ultraviolet rays. Yet I do consider Mr. Hodel's recommendation that people wear more sunglasses, hats and suntan lotion an incredible response to a very clear present and future danger that requires co-ordinated governmental action.</p>
        <p>Furthermore, I take exception to the suggestion that people use suntan lotion. There is no such thing as a healthy tan. To get effective protection from the sun's ultraviolet rays - and that means no burning or tanning - you need a sunscreen or sunblock lotion or spray with a sun protection factor (S.P.F.) of 15 or higher. STEVEN MANENTI  Greenwich, Conn., June 4, 1987</p>
      </block>
